# Ensemble CAM Project Rules

## Code Style and Formatting

### Python Code
- Use Python 3.13.2+ syntax and features
- Follow PEP 8 style guidelines
- Use type hints where appropriate
- Maximum line length: 100 characters
- Use 4 spaces for indentation
- Use descriptive variable and function names
- Add docstrings to all functions and classes

### File Organization
- Use absolute paths from project root in all scripts
- Organize imports: standard library, third-party, local imports
- Group related functionality in classes
- Keep functions focused and single-purpose

## Content Guidelines

### NO EMOJIS RULE
- **STRICTLY FORBIDDEN**: Do not use any emojis in any files, scripts, or documentation


### Documentation
- Use clear, professional language
- Provide comprehensive docstrings
- Include usage examples in documentation
- Keep README files updated and informative

### Comments
- Write clear, descriptive comments
- Explain complex logic and algorithms
- Use comments to document assumptions and constraints
- Keep comments up-to-date with code changes

## Project-Specific Rules

### Dataset Handling
- Always use absolute paths from project root
- Include progress bars for long-running operations
- Provide detailed error messages and logging
- Handle missing files gracefully
- Use pathlib.Path for path operations

### Model Training
- Include comprehensive logging and metrics
- Save model checkpoints regularly
- Provide detailed training progress information
- Use appropriate device detection (CPU/GPU/MPS)
- Include early stopping and validation

### File Naming
- Use descriptive, lowercase names with underscores
- Follow the pattern: `dataset_N_description.py` for dataset scripts
- Follow the pattern: `train_ModelName.py` for training scripts
- Use consistent naming across the project

### Error Handling
- Use try-except blocks for all external operations
- Provide meaningful error messages
- Log errors with appropriate detail levels
- Handle edge cases gracefully
- Return appropriate exit codes

## Security and Best Practices

### Sensitive Data
- NEVER hardcode API keys, tokens, or passwords
- Use environment variables for sensitive information
- Include security checks in all scripts
- Validate user inputs
- Use secure file operations

### Large Files
- Never commit large files (>100MB) to git
- Use .gitignore to exclude model weights and datasets
- Provide clear instructions for downloading large files
- Use appropriate file compression when possible

### Dependencies
- Pin dependency versions in pyproject.toml
- Use UV for package management
- Include all required dependencies
- Document optional dependencies
- Keep dependencies updated and secure

## Code Quality

### Performance
- Use appropriate data structures
- Optimize for memory usage with large datasets
- Use multiprocessing where appropriate
- Profile code for bottlenecks
- Use efficient algorithms

### Testing
- Write unit tests for core functionality
- Test edge cases and error conditions
- Use appropriate test data
- Mock external dependencies
- Maintain good test coverage

### Maintainability
- Write modular, reusable code
- Use configuration files for settings
- Provide clear interfaces between modules
- Document complex algorithms
- Keep code DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)

## Git and Version Control

### Commit Messages
- Use clear, descriptive commit messages
- Follow conventional commit format when possible
- Include relevant context in commit messages
- Reference issues or pull requests when applicable

### Branching
- Use descriptive branch names
- Keep branches focused on single features
- Delete merged branches
- Use pull requests for code review

## Documentation Standards

### README Files
- Include clear setup instructions
- Provide usage examples
- Document all dependencies
- Include troubleshooting sections
- Keep installation instructions up-to-date

### Code Documentation
- Document all public functions and classes
- Include parameter descriptions
- Provide return value documentation
- Include usage examples in docstrings
- Document exceptions that may be raised

## Project Structure

### Directory Organization
- Keep related files together
- Use consistent directory naming
- Separate source code from data and models
- Include appropriate __init__.py files
- Organize by functionality, not file type

### Import Organization
- Group imports logically
- Use absolute imports
- Avoid circular imports
- Import only what is needed
- Use aliases for long module names

## Performance and Optimization

### Memory Management
- Use generators for large datasets
- Clean up resources properly
- Use context managers for file operations
- Monitor memory usage
- Optimize data loading

### Computational Efficiency
- Use vectorized operations when possible
- Avoid unnecessary computations
- Cache expensive operations
- Use appropriate data types
- Profile and optimize bottlenecks

## Error Handling and Logging

### Logging
- Use appropriate log levels
- Include contextual information
- Log important state changes
- Use structured logging when possible
- Rotate log files appropriately

### Exception Handling
- Catch specific exceptions
- Provide meaningful error messages
- Log exceptions with context
- Handle exceptions at appropriate levels
- Use custom exceptions when needed

## Configuration Management

### Environment Variables
- Use environment variables for configuration
- Provide default values
- Validate configuration on startup
- Document all configuration options
- Use type checking for configuration

### Configuration Files
- Use standard formats (JSON, YAML, TOML)
- Validate configuration schemas
- Provide example configurations
- Document all configuration options
- Use hierarchical configuration

## Testing and Quality Assurance

### Code Quality
- Use linting tools (flake8, black, isort)
- Run type checking (mypy)
- Use code formatters consistently
- Maintain consistent code style
- Review code before committing

### Testing Strategy
- Write tests for all new functionality
- Test both success and failure cases
- Use appropriate test data
- Mock external dependencies
- Maintain good test coverage

## Deployment and Distribution

### Package Management
- Use UV for dependency management
- Pin dependency versions
- Include development dependencies
- Document installation requirements
- Provide multiple installation methods

### Distribution
- Include comprehensive documentation
- Provide clear usage instructions
- Include example configurations
- Document system requirements
- Provide troubleshooting guides

## Compliance and Standards

### Code Standards
- Follow Python PEP standards
- Use consistent naming conventions
- Maintain readable code structure
- Document complex logic
- Use appropriate design patterns

### Documentation Standards
- Keep documentation up-to-date
- Use clear, concise language
- Provide practical examples
- Include troubleshooting information
- Maintain consistent formatting

## Final Reminders

- **NO EMOJIS** in any files, scripts, or documentation
- Use professional, clear language
- Maintain consistent code style
- Document all functionality
- Handle errors gracefully
- Keep security in mind
- Optimize for performance
- Write maintainable code
- Test thoroughly
- Follow project conventions
